John Edwards: Foreign language skills are essential for global citizens
Private schools in Scotland maintain their academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with a rewarding stream of academic achievements, strengthened both individually and collectively in terms of sport, art, music and community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, which are sponsored by the Scots Private Schools Council (SCIS), are working to deliver the best quality of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to equip students with deep and broad knowledge, as well as career orientation and status as global citizens.
As an education subdiscipline that can design and run the school’s unique curriculum, we see modern foreign languages continuing to be a popular and chosen topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in the language he understands, what he says goes into his mind.
If you talk to him in his own language, what he says will come into his heart.”
This is a convincing message that we don’t rely solely on English when it comes to establishing relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From recent exams this year, we can see that foreign languages are leading the charts with the best grades in private school subjects.
A total of 68 percent of foreign language students scored higher than A.
Data collected from the 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students scored more than an A in Chinese, while 72 percent learned German, 69 percent learned French, and 63 percent learned Spanish.
This suggests that Scottish private schools are moving towards treating foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will not be able to miss in the future.
Elective language courses are being considered as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) majors in private school programs as well as elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Skills and Occupations Council in 2014 found that one of the reasons employers have difficulty finding people is a lack of language skills.
Therefore, foreign language skills are becoming more practical in order to equip young people to enter the professional practice in the future.
With more and more opportunities for foreign language career prospects, these skills become practical in an increasingly flat world.
No matter how people choose to work, if they learn a second language, they will gain a real advantage in the future by having such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly in the language of the native speakers, a polyglot will obviously lead every challenge.
According to a YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to practice a simple assembly in another foreign language, and French was the only foreign language to account for a unit-row number, 15 percent.
That’s why investing in foreign language teaching is essential for children today.
Being multilingual, especially in the languages of developing economies, will equip children with the brighter potential to find a real job.
In Scotland, each school teaches different languages.
Some schools will focus on more modern foreign languages, while others will teach foreign languages that are considered important for the UK in the 2020 vision, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever children are interested in, there are a variety of foreign languages to choose from in private schools, along with a team of teachers with expertise in the profession.
Private schools in Scotland focus on providing an academic environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
There is no denying that, in an international business environment, foreign languages will continue to be extremely important to the future of the country, this should be replicated in education.
In fact, modern foreign languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Private schools will continue to offer this opportunity to Scottish youth: diversity and excellence.
There's no other choice.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Private School Council.
