North Korea says 'no way' unilateral disarmament in lack of trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the sanctions are still being maintained and deepening its distrust of the United States and that there is no way the country will unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho, speaking at the United Nations General Assembly's annual session, said North Korea had taken "many goodwill measures" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test bases and pledging not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we don't see the same move from the US side," he said.
“If we can’t trust the U.S. side, we won’t be able to guarantee our national security with confidence, and in such a situation, there is no way that we will unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri echoed North Korea’s familiar complaint that Washington refuses to dismantle its nuclear weapons “in stages” and that North Korea will reap the corresponding benefits of doing so step by step, his remarks this time have a notable point of not refusing to unilaterally dismantle nuclear weapons as Pyongyang has previously refused.
Ri refers to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an incumbent U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12. In this statement, Kim pledged to work towards "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula," while Trump promised security guarantees for North Korea.
North Korea is still trying to find a way to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States insists that Pyongyang give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also opposes calls for easing harsh international sanctions against Tien.
“The United States insists on ‘disarmament of nuclear weapons first’ and increases pressure with sanctions to achieve its objectives in a coercive manner, even opposing the ‘declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can put us on our knees is just the dream of those who don’t understand us.
But the problem here is that the sanctions that are still in place continue to lose our trust.”
Ri made no mention of plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump as the U.S. leader presented at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he referred to three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the disarmament negotiator is South Korea, not the United States, then the denuclearization talks on the Korean Peninsula will not go to a standstill.”
However, Ri’s tone was different from last year, when he told the General Assembly that North Korea’s missile launch on the U.S. mainland was inevitable in a suicide mission after Trump called Kim “Rocket Man.”
Last year at the United Nations, Trump threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for taking courageous steps to disarm it, but he stressed that much work remains to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a deadline for the move: “Two years, three years, five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its efforts.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council sanctions must continue to be enforced in a strong and uncompromising manner until we can confirm the results of complete denuclearization, finally, with verifiable evidence.”
The Security Council has agreed to intensify sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to block funding for its nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo held talks with Ri on the sidelines of official U.N. General Assembly meetings and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the final results were not very promising.
He left Pyongyang after a visit in July and said the talks had made certain progress, but only hours later North Korea accused the foreign minister of making “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea has pledged to hold a meeting with South Korean President Moon Jae-in this month to dismantle a missile test base and a nuclear complex if the United States makes a “similar move.”
