Harvard students take a full rest course
In an effort to combat a culture of machine-pressured learning, with night owl students drinking coffee instead of water, a new course at Harvard University this year has encouraged all college students to sleep more.
Research students at this world’s number one university often don’t know the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, designed the course and he himself believes it is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for starting this course came after he took part in a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on the learning process.
“At the end of the talk, a student came up to me and said, ‘Why didn’t you know this until the last year?’
She said no one had told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students the importance of good sleep habits that improve academic and athletic performance, while also improving their overall health.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the school decided to introduce the course after finding students with severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course covers a wide range of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a dorm room image in which students can click on coffee cups, curtains, workout machines and books to learn about the effects of caffeine, how light and sleep deprivation affect the results of exercise, as well as the importance of forming a bedtime routine.
In another part, participants were examined how long-term sleep deprivation could increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then the university campus map, with interactive symbols, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that this course cannot immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” Czeisler added.
He said the "night owl student" pride culture still exists, while modern technologies and increasing pressure on students lead to sleep deprivation being an increasingly serious problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, good quality sleep should become a student’s ‘secret weapon’ to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety – even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep puts the brain into a state of hunger, leading us to be constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying biology, chemistry and physics, helped Czeisler design the course and took one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course helped him ‘open his eyes’ and inspired him to make an effort to call for a course throughout the school.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to join a similar program before starting to compete in the main course.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students consider when setting alarms for bedtime and waking hours, while also being aware of the harmful effects of ‘blue light’ emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble sleeping.
